Raw dev notes -- The Flicker Nightmare and v2.2.0 Release

Okay, so this past few months have been a wild ride getting `smart-hebrew-rtl` to a state I'm actually proud of, especially with the v2.2.0 release. This project is my little passion side-project, a browser extension designed to intelligently detect and reformat Hebrew text on various web platforms, making it display correctly Right-to-Left (RTL) without breaking the surrounding English or other languages. The goal is to make reading Hebrew online a seamless experience, especially on dynamic, AI-driven chat platforms where content streams in.

The big push started with a complete rewrite for `v2.2.0-dev` back in December. The old approach was just not cutting it for real-time streaming content – it was slow and, frankly, ugly. The main goal for this period was to achieve *instant* and *flicker-free* RTL rendering. This turned out to be a much bigger beast than I anticipated. I tried everything: "sticky CSS," applying native `dir` attributes, flushing orphaned mutations, and eventually landed on a "two-phase streaming RTL" approach. Each fix seemed to solve one problem only to reveal another, like a whack-a-mole game. The flicker was persistent, a real thorn in my side.

Beyond the flicker, I hit some classic browser extension gotchas. Chrome rejected my dev manifest because of non-numeric suffixes (who knew?), and I had to strip out a `_comment` key to suppress warnings. More critically, I ran into a nasty bug where the extension would freeze input fields on platforms like ChatGPT. Turns out, observing `characterData` mutations was the culprit – it was just too aggressive and caused a deadlock or something similar. I had to completely remove that observer and implement smarter filtering to skip *all* mutations from editable areas. This was a huge "aha!" moment, realizing that sometimes less observation is more.

To really get a handle on the streaming issues, I built a whole diagnostic tool using Chrome DevTools Protocol (CDP). This thing was invaluable for cross-platform testing, letting me simulate different rendering speeds and inspect the DOM changes in detail. I had to harden it with "stealth flags" and make it survive single-page application (SPA) navigations. It helped me pinpoint specific selectors for platforms like Claude.ai, which has its own unique DOM structure for "artifacts" and streaming content. Getting Claude.ai's TXT artifacts to render correctly, even overriding its native RTL threshold, was a mini-victory in itself, involving iframe handlers and hybrid fixes.

Finally, there was the polish and release prep. Updating the popup with a GitHub link, then a Hebrew name, then removing the Hebrew name for a feedback link (decisions, decisions!). Drafting and refining the Chrome Web Store description to accurately reflect the new "flicker-free streaming" capabilities was a task in itself. And, of course, adding a post-update notification banner in the popup, translated to Hebrew, to highlight the major improvements. Reorganizing the project structure, moving docs and tools out of the main extension package, and adding copyright headers felt like the final touches on a long journey.

Honestly, this period felt like a marathon. There were moments of pure frustration, staring at a flickering screen, wondering why my carefully crafted CSS or MutationObserver logic wasn't working. But there was also immense satisfaction in slowly chipping away at these complex rendering problems, learning so much about browser internals and the nuances of DOM manipulation. It reinforced the lesson that sometimes you need to build your own tools to understand and solve a problem, and that persistence, even when you feel like you're going in circles, eventually pays off. Shipping v2.2.0 feels like a huge weight off my shoulders, and I'm genuinely excited for users to experience the smoother, more reliable RTL.

Next: Monitor feedback and plan for minor bug fixes.
